  "article": [
   "Start with the favorite. A week ago the model gave Rawhides 64.7% to win the City Championship; tonight that number jumped to 79.5% \u2014 a 14.8-point rise and another sharp move up. The daylight behind them is becoming a canyon.",
   "They got there by booking the winners'-bracket final: Rawhides beat Hall Monitors 9-7 and Bus Stop beat Pocket Fizz 9-7. The A-side title match is set \u2014 Rawhides vs Bus Stop \u2014 and it carries a double-elimination twist: the winner walks into the grand final with a safety net (the losers'-bracket survivor has to beat them twice), while the loser is knocked to the one-loss side. Bus Stop climbed to 15% as the second-most-likely champion \u2014 distant, but real.",
   "The night's gut-punch landed on the losers' side \u2014 and it was the end of an era. El Farolito ended Pilsner's season 9-6, and with it one of the great runs in City Championship history. For six-plus seasons the InnDecisives never fell out of the top two; their all-time playoff record is 17-7, and the number that defined the dynasty is 15-0 \u2014 their mark against everyone who wasn't the Rawhides. For years you did not beat Pilsner. Rawhides beat Pilsner, and nobody else got a turn.",
   "This was supposed to be the redemption year. Evan Burgess, their 576-rated ace, had spent the first half of the season playing down with a junior team as its coach \u2014 he was always coming back for the playoffs, and it was his absence from the standings, not from the roster, that stuck a team this good with the 6-seed. He returned, the lineup was whole, and for a while the old magic held. But here is the cruelest detail: for the first time anyone can remember, Pilsner's season didn't end against Rawhides. They fell one rung short of even reaching the rival the whole bracket was bending toward. Six seasons of inevitability, gone quietly in the one-loss bracket. Pour one out for the InnDecisives.",
   "There was a Cinderella in the wreckage, too, and midnight finally came: Marcelo's ended Route 101's run 9-2. But what a run it was. The 12th-seed Dalmatians knocked off a top seed in the opening round and then flat refused to lose a close one \u2014 both of their wins were 9-8 heart-stoppers that made the smart money sweat for weeks. The glass slipper doesn't fit anymore, but the Dalmatians danced a lot longer than a 12th seed has any right to.",
   "Hall Monitors and Pocket Fizz survive but drop to the losers' bracket, where one more slip ends it. 6 teams remain. For Rawhides, only the winners'-bracket final stands between them and the grand final."
  ]
 },
